  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Balance Island</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">In many delta areas, salinity issues play a role that will only get bigger in the future due to climate change and sea level rise. This puts fresh water reserves under pressure. This has major implications for agriculture, for household or industrial use of river water, the intake of drinking water, and the natural ecosystem, which requires expensive compensatory measures. By constructing a Balance Island (a sand body), however, the flow can be influenced in such a way that the mixing zone of fresh and salt water is moved more seaward. This limits the salinization of the hinterland. Initial calculations for the Dutch situation (Haringvliet) have shown that the costs are lower than the compensatory measures, and that additional quality of use can be added, such as protection of the coastline, development of living environment for special animals and plants, new opportunities for tourism and recreation, and new economic activities such as aquaculture. Partners for Water has granted an incidental subsidy to further investigate this concept in the Mekong Delta (pre-feasibility). This pre-feasibility has provided useful knowledge about the application of the Balance Island concept in other deltas. The study has also shown that the situation in the Mekong Delta Balance Island is technically and cost-technically not feasible.</narrative>
  </description>
